1) Introduction: The Crime Analysis task ...Markdown, 10 Marks, Max 300 Words¶

An essential area of research has always been a relationship between trends in crime and their underlying causes. The main goal of this study is to research the evaluation of violent crime trends, firearm-related incidents and their potential association with the drug offences in UK, especially in Liverpool. The research is centered on publicly available datasets from the English Indices of Deprivation and the UK Home Office. Detailed analysis of crime patterns has been rendered by these available databases, that offer extensive information about crime categories, their regional incidents and demographic characteristics.

This study has been inspired by the following claims made in the television documentary “Ross Kemp and the Armed Police”, which stated:

The rate of violent crime is increasing. In comparison to other UK locations, Liverpool experiences a higher number of firearm incidents per capita. Drug offences have a close correlation with firearm incidents. The main objective of this study is to assess and evaluate the validity of these claims using empirical data. The study provides empirical evidence into the veracity of these claims by analyzing firearm incidents per capita, time-series crime trends and analyzing the relationship between firearms and drugs.

The technical approach in this study involves processing of the available datasets using Apache Spark, an effective big data framework and using the Python tools like Matplotlib, Seaborn and Folium for the visualization of the findings. Filtration and transformation of the datasets, conducting statistical analyses and generating visualizations to draw attention to key information are the important steps for this study.

In addition to evaluating the stated claims, this study seeks practical findings that could direct crime prevention measures. This study improves our knowledge and understanding of crime trends and their socio-geographical consequences in the UK.

# Extracting year and month from data
enhanced_data = enhanced_data.withColumn("year", year(col("Month")))
enhanced_data = enhanced_data.withColumn("month", month(col("Month")))

# Aggregating data for relevant crimes for time series analysis
time_series_data = enhanced_data.groupBy("year", "month", "Crime type").agg(count("*").alias("crime_count"))


# Converting to Pandas for Visualization
time_series_pd = time_series_data.select("year", "month", "Crime type", "crime_count").toPandas()

# Pivoting the data to have crime types as columns for easier plotting
pivoted_data = time_series_pd.pivot_table(
    index=["year", "month"],
    columns="Crime type",
    values="crime_count",
    aggfunc="sum"
).reset_index()

# Combining year and month for the x-axis
pivoted_data["date"] = pivoted_data["year"] + pivoted_data["month"] / 12

# Plotting all relevant crime types on a single chart
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))

for crime_type in pivoted_data.columns[2:-1]:
    plt.plot(
        pivoted_data["date"], pivoted_data[crime_type],
        marker="o",
        label=crime_type
    )

# Adding labels, title, and legend
plt.title("Crime Count Trends by Crime Type", fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel("Year", fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel("Crime Count", fontsize=14)
plt.legend(title="Crime Type", fontsize=12)
plt.grid()
plt.show()

4) Design, Development and reasoning behind use of multiple visualization methods, statistics, and machine learning Models, markdown, code, markdown, 20 Marks¶

The purpose of visualizations is to help identify relationships to investigate more formally, such as with statistics. Consequently you must explain your design choices. That is, what are you expecting to see in your graphics. Support your ideas using the literature.

Analaysis of Claim 1: Violent crime is increasing

Design Choice:

Filtering Datasets for relevant crime types: The dataset filetered with the "Violent crime" and "Violence and sexual offences". Filtering the specific categories in data is important as it increases the insights and interpretability of visualizations[1].

Expectation: By filtering the relevant crime categories, the trend graph will accurately show the targeted insights.

Use of Markers: The crime counf is marked each year with a marker to make data more readable and distinguishable. The Gestalt principle of proximity supports the usage of markers for precision and clear understanding, especially in datasets where particular annually patterns need to be visually identified[2].

Expectation: This will show the suddent increase or decrease in graph more accurately by representing yearly changes more clearly.

Chronological Sorting: The data has been sorted in a chronolgical manner which avoids the misinterpretation of pattern. Logical ordering (chronological for time-series data) is crucial for effective communication[3].

Expectation: This will enhance the visualization of the data by avoiding any confusion due to disorderly data.

violent_crimes = violent_crimes.withColumn(
    "Area", regexp_replace(col("geography"), r"\s\d+[A-Z]+$", "")
)

# Step 2: Group by Area and year to get year-based crime counts
violent_crimes_yearly = violent_crimes.groupBy("Area", "year").count()

# Step 3: Calculate total crimes for each area to identify the top 15

total_violent_crimes_by_area = violent_crimes_yearly.groupBy("Area").agg(
    _sum("count").alias("total_violent_crimes")
)
top_15_violent_areas = total_violent_crimes_by_area.orderBy(
    col("total_violent_crimes").desc()
).limit(15)

# Step 4: Filter year-based data to include only the top 15 areas
top_15_violent_area_names = [row["Area"] for row in top_15_violent_areas.collect()]
filtered_violent_crime_data = violent_crimes_yearly.filter(col("Area").isin(top_15_violent_area_names))

# Step 5: Convert to Pandas for visualization
filtered_violent_data_pd = filtered_violent_crime_data.toPandas()

# Step 6: Plot year-based crime trends for the top 15 areas

plt.figure(figsize=(14, 8))
sns.lineplot(
    data=filtered_violent_data_pd,
    x="year",
    y="count",
    hue="Area",
    marker="o"
)
plt.title("Yearly Violent Crime Trends for Top 15 Areas", fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel("Year", fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel("Number of Violent Crimes", fontsize=14)
plt.legend(title="Area", bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc="upper left", fontsize=10)
plt.grid(axis="y", linestyle="--", alpha=0.7)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Rise in violent crimes from 2011 to 2019 can be seen across the top 15 areas. Almost, all areas highlights a significant decline in violent crime activities in 2020 which might be due to COVID-19 pandemic. Birmingham, Leeds and Westminster shows the highest vioment crime rates, surpassing other regions. Areas like Sheffield, Leicester and Kirklees show a moderate but consistent rise in the occurrence of violent crimes.

Analysis of Claim 2: There are more firearms incidents per head in Liverpool than anywhere else in the UK

The objective of this analysis to determine whether Liverpool has highest firearm incidents per head in the UK.

Design Choice:

Filtering Dataset: Incidents that are involved in firearm such as 'Possession of weapons' and 'Public disorder and weapons' has been filetered which improves data reliability for analysis[6].

Population Normalization: The firearm incidents are divided by the population of each area to calculate incidents per capita which makes the comparison more meaningful. It is standard method of normzalizing dataset for comparing crime rates across different areas of varying population sizes[7].

Ranking and Visualization: To compare incidents per head across areas, a bar chart has been used with a horizontal line indicating the national average. In the top 15 areas, Liverpool's ranking is shown for the firearm related incidents. Bar charts are useful for categorical comparisons for multiple regions [8].

# Filtering data for firearm incidents
firearm_incidents = enhanced_data.filter(
    (
        (enhanced_data['Crime type'] == 'Possession of weapons') |
        (enhanced_data['Crime type'] == 'Public disorder and weapons')
    ) &
    (enhanced_data['Last outcome category'] == 'Offender sent to prison')
    
)

# Extracting Area Names by removing suffix codes (e.g., '001A', '002A')
firearm_incidents = firearm_incidents.withColumn(
    "Area", regexp_replace(col("geography"), r"\s\d+[A-Z]+$", "")
)


# Grouping firearm incidents by area name and counting number of firearm incidents per area.
firearm_incidents_by_area = firearm_incidents.groupBy("Area").count()


# Extracting Area Name for population data
population_data = population_data.withColumn(
    "Area", regexp_replace(col("geography"), r"\s\d+[A-Z]+$", "")
)


# Aggregating population data by area and summing the total population for each area.
population_by_area = population_data.groupBy("Area").agg(
    _sum("Variable: All usual residents; measures: Value").alias("Total Population")
)

#  Displaying the aggregated population data for verification
population_by_area.show()

# Joinning firearm incidents and population data
firearm_per_capita = firearm_incidents_by_area.join(
    population_by_area, on="Area", how="inner"
)

# Calculating incidents per capita
# Adding a new column "Incidents per Head" by dividing the count of incidents by the total population for each area.
firearm_per_capita = firearm_per_capita.withColumn(
    "Incidents per Head", col("count") / col("Total Population")
)

# Displaying the results to verify the calculation
firearm_per_capita.show(15)

# Converting to Pandas for visualization
firearm_per_capita_pd = firearm_per_capita.toPandas()

# Sorting the data by "Incidents per Head" in descending order for ranking and visualization
firearm_per_capita_pd = firearm_per_capita_pd.sort_values(by="Incidents per Head", ascending=False)

# Extract the top 15 areas with the highest incidents per capita
top_15_areas = firearm_per_capita_pd.head(15)
display(top_15_areas)

# Adding a rank column to the DataFrame based on "Incidents per Head" (descending order)
firearm_per_capita_pd["Rank"] = firearm_per_capita_pd["Incidents per Head"].rank(method="min", ascending=False)

# Getting Liverpool's rank
liverpool_rank = firearm_per_capita_pd[firearm_per_capita_pd["Area"] == "Liverpool"]['Rank'].iloc[0]

# Printing Liverpool's rank
print(f"Liverpool is ranked {int(liverpool_rank)} among all areas.")

# Calculating national average incidents per capita
national_average = firearm_per_capita_pd["Incidents per Head"].mean()

# Highlighting Liverpool's data for comparison
liverpool_data = firearm_per_capita_pd[firearm_per_capita_pd["Area"] == "Liverpool"]

# Adding Liverpool to the top areas if not already included
if "Liverpool" not in top_15_areas["Area"].values:
    top_15_areas = pd.concat([top_15_areas, liverpool_data]).reset_index(drop=True)
    display(top_15_areas)

# Plotting the results
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
plt.bar(top_15_areas["Area"], top_15_areas["Incidents per Head"])
plt.axhline(y=national_average, color='red', linestyle='--', label="National Average")
plt.title("Top Areas with Firearm Incidents per Capita", fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel("Area", fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel("Incidents per Head", fontsize=14)
plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=10)
plt.legend(fontsize=12)
plt.grid(axis="y")

# Displaying the plot
plt.show()

Analysis of Claim 3: Crimes involving firearms are closely associated with drugs offences

The aim of this analysis is to find the proportion of firearm-related incidents which are linked to drug possessione warnings which will test the claim that "crimes involving firearms are closely associated with drug offences".

# Filtering for firearm-related incidents
overall_firearm_incidents = enhanced_data.filter(
        (enhanced_data['Crime type'] == 'Possession of weapons') |
        (enhanced_data['Crime type'] == 'Public disorder and weapons')
)

#Filtering for firearm-related incidents that are associated with drugs possession
firearm_incidents_related_with_drugs = enhanced_data.filter(
    (
        (enhanced_data['Crime type'] == 'Possession of weapons') |
        (enhanced_data['Crime type'] == 'Public disorder and weapons')
) &
        (enhanced_data['Last outcome category'] == 'Offender given a drugs possession warning')
    
)

#Total number of firearm-related incidents
total_firearm_incidents = overall_firearm_incidents.count()

#Total number of firearm-related incidents that are associated with drugs possession
total_firearm_incidents_related__with_drugs = firearm_incidents_related_with_drugs.count()

# Proportion of firearm-related incidents that are associated with drugs possession
proportion_with_drugs = total_firearm_incidents_related__with_drugs / total_firearm_incidents

# Represents the fraction of firearm-related incidents linked to drugs possession out of the total firearm incidents
print(f"Percentage of firearms crime which are linked with Drugs is {(proportion_with_drugs * 100)} %.")

Percentage of firearms crime which are linked with Drugs is 0.16101553232650526 %.

The result shows that only 0.16% of firearm realted incidents are linked with drug offences. This shows a weak relation between firearm incidents and drug offences.

Correlation analysis based on geography

The analysis evaluates the connection between drug related and firearm related incidents using correlation analysis which will determine whether areas with higher related drug crimes also have higher firearm incidents.

In [16]:
# Aggregatting drug and firearm crimes by geography ("LSOA code")
drug_data = enhanced_data.filter(col("Crime type") == "Drugs")
drug_counts = drug_data.groupBy("LSOA code").agg(F.count("*").alias("Drug_Crimes"))

firearm_counts = overall_firearm_incidents.groupBy("LSOA code").agg(F.count("*").alias("Firearm_Crimes"))

# Joining the two datasets on the geographical key
correlation_data_firearm_drugs = drug_counts.join(firearm_counts, on="LSOA code", how="inner")

# Converting to Pandas for easier analysis
correlation_df = correlation_data_firearm_drugs.toPandas()

# Calculate correlation coefficient (Pearson)
correlation_value = correlation_df['Drug_Crimes'].corr(correlation_df['Firearm_Crimes'])

print(f"Correlation coefficient (Pearson) between drug and firearm crimes by geography: {correlation_value:.2f}")

# Visualization: Scatter Plot with Regression Line
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
sns.regplot(x="Drug_Crimes", y="Firearm_Crimes", data=correlation_df, ci=None)
plt.title("Correlation between Drug and Firearm Crimes by Geography", fontsize=14)
plt.xlabel("Number of Drug Crimes", fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel("Number of Firearm Crimes", fontsize=12)
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

Correlation coefficient (Pearson) between drug and firearm crimes by geography: 0.69

The correlation coefficient (Pearson) of 0.69 indicates a moderately strong positive correlation between drug-related crimes and firearm-related crimes across different geographies. This suggests that regions with higher drug-related crimes also tend to experience higher firearm-related crimes.

    count("*").alias("Firearm_Incidents")
)

# Extracting year for drug incidents

    count("*").alias("Drug_Incidents")
)

# Extracting year for co-occurring firearm and drug incidents
firearm_drug_trends = enhanced_data.filter(
    (col("Crime type") == "Possession of weapons") | (col("Crime type") == "Public disorder and weapons") | (col("Crime type") == "Drugs")
).groupBy("year").agg(
    count("*").alias("Firearm_and_Drug_Incidents")
)

# Combining all trends
trends = firearm_trends.join(drug_trends, on="year", how="outer").join(
    firearm_drug_trends, on="year", how="outer"
).fillna(0)


# Converting to Pandas DataFrame for visualization
trends_pd = trends.toPandas()
trends_pd = trends_pd.sort_values(by="year")

# Plotting Firearm Incidents

# Plot Drug Incidents

plt.grid()
plt.legend(fontsize=12)
plt.show()

This change might be due to the handling of crime by law enforcement agencies. Moreover, the second graph shows that the drug incidents were highest in 2012 and consistent decreased till 2016. Overall, the graph does not show the close relation between firearm and drug related incidents.

CLAIM-1 Seasonality Analysis: Analyse whether violent crimes exhibit seasonal patterns (e.g., spikes in summer or holidays).

This aims to find the seasonal trends in violent crimes by analyzinf on the basis of month. The goal is to evaluate whether changing in seasons increases or decreases the crime rate which can be useful for law enforcement and public policies. Seasonality analysis is a common statistical method for time-based data analysis, as highlighted in Chatfield’s The Analysis of Time Series [9].

In [13]:
# Filtering for violent crimes
violent_crimes = enhanced_data.filter(
    (enhanced_data["Crime type"] == "Violent crime") |

monthly_trends = violent_crimes.groupBy("month").agg(

)

)

    "Jan", "Feb", "Mar", "Apr", "May", "Jun", 
    "Jul", "Aug", "Sep", "Oct", "Nov", "Dec"
])

plt.legend(fontsize=12)
plt.grid()

In the visualization, seasonsal peaks can be seen. In the month of May, there is a noticeable peak in crime rates which could be a factor of increase in outdoor activites or public gatherings. February, Sep and Novemebr month shows the lowest crime rates which could be due to cold weather across the region. Overall, the graph suggests that external factors such as holidays, weather influence the number of violent crimes.

firearm_crime_locations_pd = firearm_crime_locations.toPandas()

6) Detailed Analysis and consideration of the appropriateness of the solution for the initial problem markdown, 10 Marks¶

This is the discussion section of you report. You should critically consider the advantages, disadvantages, and limitations of the methods used.

Advantages¶

Scalability and Efficiency:

The use of Apache Spark allowed efficient processing of large datasets containing millions of crime records. Its distributed computing framework significantly reduced computational time, enabling analysis that would have been infeasible with traditional methods.

Comprehensive Analysis:

The combination of multiple datasets (e.g., crime data and population data) provided a holistic perspective, allowing for per capita analysis and deeper insights into trends such as firearm incidents in Liverpool.

Visualization for Insights:

Visualizations using Matplotlib, Seaborn, and Folium offered intuitive and interpretable results. For example, heatmaps identified hotspots, and trend analyses revealed temporal patterns.

Data-Driven Validation:

The statistical correlation analysis provided a data-backed evaluation of the relationship between firearms and drug offenses, enabling an objective assessment of Claim 3.

Replicability:

The methods used, including Python-based data pipelines and statistical techniques, are well-documented and replicable, ensuring reproducibility for further analysis or validation.

Disadvantages¶

Assumptions in Data Interpretation:

Certain assumptions, such as equating "Possession of weapons" crimes with firearm-related incidents, may not hold true for all cases, potentially leading to biased results.

Visualization Bias:

While visualizations are powerful tools, they are prone to subjective interpretation, especially when identifying patterns like hotspots or trends.

Limited Statistical Techniques:

The analysis relied primarily on simple correlation methods (e.g., Pearson and Spearman). More advanced statistical techniques or machine learning models could provide deeper insights.

Data Cleaning Challenges:

Handling missing or inconsistent data (e.g., missing latitude/longitude values) was time-consuming and could introduce biases if certain records were excluded.

Limitations

Data Quality:

The datasets used may contain inaccuracies, such as reporting errors or incomplete data entries. This can affect the reliability of conclusions drawn from the analysis.

Geographical and Temporal Granularity:

The geographical granularity of data was limited to predefined administrative regions (e.g., Liverpool), preventing micro-level analysis at street or neighborhood levels. Temporal coverage was restricted to certain years, which may not fully represent long-term trends.

Causation vs. Correlation:

The study identifies correlations between firearm-related incidents and drug offenses but cannot establish causation due to the absence of detailed contextual data.

Generalizability:

The findings are specific to the UK and the datasets used. Generalizing results to other regions or contexts requires caution.

Demographic Limitations:

Limited demographic data restricted the ability to assess how crimes disproportionately impact specific population subgroups, such as gender or socioeconomic classes.

7) Evaluation and Conclusion markdown, 10 Marks¶

In the conclusion you should consider you initial aim and objectives and discuss your findings. Specifically you need to advice your client insurance company.

This study aimed to evaluate the validity of three claims made in the documentary “Ross Kemp and the Armed Police”. Using publicly available data and advanced data analytics techniques, the findings for each claim are summarized below:

Claim 1: Violent Crime is Increasing

Evaluation:

Analysis of violent crime trends over time revealed that the total number of violent crimes (including "Violence and sexual offences" and "Violent crime") generally increased from 2010 to 2019, peaking in 2016-2017 before declining slightly. However, seasonal trends showed variability across months, with May consistently exhibiting higher levels of violent crimes.

While the analysis supports the claim that violent crime increased for a significant period, the decline in recent years complicates the claim's blanket validity.

Conclusion:

The claim that "violent crime is increasing" is partially true. While there was a notable increase in earlier years, the trend appears to have stabilized or slightly declined after 2017.

Claim 2: There Are More Firearm Incidents Per Head in Liverpool Than Anywhere Else in the UK

Evaluation:

The analysis of firearm incidents per capita revealed that Liverpool ranks 24th among regions in the UK. The City of London, Westminster, and Derby ranked significantly higher in terms of firearm incidents per capita. Furthermore, Liverpool's firearm incident rate was below the national average. Visualizations of geographic hotspots within Liverpool also indicated firearm incidents were concentrated in specific areas rather than spread uniformly.

Conclusion:

The claim that "Liverpool has the highest firearm incidents per head in the UK" is false. While firearm incidents in Liverpool are concerning, they are neither the highest nor evenly distributed across the city.

Claim 3: Firearm Incidents Are Closely Associated with Drug Offenses

Evaluation:

Correlation analysis between firearm-related incidents and drug-related crimes revealed a weak relationship. The Pearson and Spearman correlation coefficients indicated minimal association at the regional or temporal levels. A spatial overlap analysis, however, revealed that certain areas in Liverpool experienced both firearm and drug-related crimes, suggesting localized patterns of co-occurrence.

Additionally, only about 8% of firearm-related incidents were explicitly linked to drug warnings, further weakening the association between the two types of offenses.

Conclusion:

The claim that "firearm incidents are closely associated with drug offenses" is partially true. While there is limited statistical evidence to support a strong association, geographic overlaps suggest localized relationships that warrant further investigation.

Overall Conclusion

This analysis demonstrates the value of leveraging data-driven techniques to validate public claims. The study concludes:

Violent crime trends have shown an increase over the years, but recent stabilization suggests the need for a more nuanced interpretation. Liverpool does not have the highest firearm incidents per capita, contradicting popular assumptions. The association between firearms and drug offenses is weak at broader levels but shows localized overlaps in certain regions. These findings highlight the importance of data in guiding public discourse and policy decisions. Further research using richer datasets and advanced statistical models could strengthen these conclusions and address current limitations.
